## JavaScript Overview

**JavaScript** is the language of the web -- it runs in every browser.

**Key Concepts:**
- Variables: let, const, var
- Functions: regular, arrow (=>), async/await
- DOM: document.getElementById(), querySelector()
- Events: addEventListener('click', handler)
- Fetch API: making HTTP requests to REST APIs

**Quick Fetch Example:**
```javascript
const sendMessage = async (msg) => {
  const res = await fetch('/api/chat', {
    method: 'POST',
    headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
    body: JSON.stringify({ message: msg })
  });
  const data = await res.json();
  console.log(data.text);
};
sendMessage('hello');
```

## CSS (Cascading Style Sheets)

CSS controls the **visual presentation** of HTML elements.

**Key Concepts:**
- **Box Model:** margin, border, padding, content
- **Flexbox:** 1D layout (display: flex)
- **Grid:** 2D layout (display: grid)
- **CSS Variables:** --accent-color: #d97757
- **Media Queries:** responsive breakpoints

**Example:**
```css
:root {
  --primary: #d97757;
}

.chat-form {
  display: flex;
  gap: 12px;
  align-items: center;
}

@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .sidebar { display: none; }
}
```

## Node.js and Express

**Node.js** runs JavaScript on the server side.
**Express** is a lightweight web framework for Node.

**Setup:**
```bash
npm init -y
npm install express cors
```

**Simple REST Server:**
```javascript
const express = require('express');
const app = express();
app.use(express.json());

let history = [];

app.get('/api/history', (req, res) => res.json(history));

app.post('/api/chat', (req, res) => {
  const { message } = req.body;
  const reply = { sender: 'bot', text: 'Got: ' + message };
  history.push(reply);
  res.json(reply);
});

app.listen(3000, () => console.log('Running on port 3000'));
```

## Databases Overview

**Relational (SQL):** data in tables with rows and columns
- Examples: MySQL, PostgreSQL, SQLite

**Non-Relational (NoSQL):** flexible document or key-value storage
- Examples: MongoDB, Redis, Firebase

**SQL Quick Reference:**
```sql
CREATE TABLE users (
  id    INTEGER PRIMARY KEY,
  name  TEXT NOT NULL,
  email TEXT UNIQUE
);

INSERT INTO users (name, email) VALUES ('Alice', 'a@email.com');
SELECT * FROM users WHERE name = 'Alice';
UPDATE users SET email = 'new@email.com' WHERE id = 1;
DELETE FROM users WHERE id = 1;
```

## Sorting Algorithms

| Algorithm   | Best       | Average    | Worst      | Space    |
|-------------|------------|------------|------------|----------|
| Bubble Sort | O(n)       | O(n2)      | O(n2)      | O(1)     |
| Merge Sort  | O(n log n) | O(n log n) | O(n log n) | O(n)     |
| Quick Sort  | O(n log n) | O(n log n) | O(n2)      | O(log n) |

**Quick Sort in JavaScript:**
```javascript
function quickSort(arr) {
  if (arr.length <= 1) return arr;
  const pivot = arr[Math.floor(arr.length / 2)];
  const left  = arr.filter(x => x < pivot);
  const mid   = arr.filter(x => x === pivot);
  const right = arr.filter(x => x > pivot);
  return [...quickSort(left), ...mid, ...quickSort(right)];
}
console.log(quickSort([3,1,4,1,5,9,2,6]));
// Output: [1,1,2,3,4,5,6,9]
```
